INSERT INTO `articles` VALUES(3, 'img/articles/michael_stevens_world_of_mobile_first.jpg', 'The World of &#147;Mobile First&#148;', 'Lets discuss buzz words', 'When you get into a room and you start discussing the concept of going &#147;Mobile First&#148; with a group of people, you might assume that\r\n		everyone is thinking the way you are, but you&#146;d be wrong.', '<div class="inner-container">\r\n	<h3>So what is "Mobile First"?</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		One important thing to remember is that the term “mobile first” can literally mean different things depending on who you are talking to.\r\n		Since, my primary profession is that of a User Experience Designer I have often approached this concept from a design standpoint, but over the years\r\n		I have come to see how others might interrupt it.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<strong>Developers</strong> may view going &#147;Mobile First&#148; as choosing faster technologies that will insure higher performance over low bandwidth connections.\r\n		So when a designer delivers a concept loaded with huge images, but where the interactions are mobile friendly, but the resources required to build it aren''t; you\r\n		might get some blow back that you aren''t being &#147;Mobile First&#148; even though you&#146;ve design with mobile in mind.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<strong>Business Owners/Stakeholders</strong> may see mobile first in many various lights, never will two clients have the same perspective or expectations around what they expect from you.\r\n		To one client going &#147;Mobile First&#148; may mean that they need to get a mobile only website in place first before they build out their desktop experience. To another it may mean investing\r\n		in mobile applications, but not mobile web. And finally some have the perspective that before they roll anything to their &#147;time &amp; tested&#148; desktop site they need to test it out on their smaller mobile.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		And finally...\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<strong>Designers</strong> often see this concept as the start of their design process. They start with the mobile designs before moving on to the larger desktop versions of their sites. I have seen many examples where the \r\n		designer will design both solution at the same time, but not in relation to each other. In many cases there are still often huge differences between the two executions, but because they provided a mobile solution they view their\r\n		process as being &#147;Mobile First&#148;\r\n	</p>\r\n	<h3>Confused yet?</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Well you might be saying... &#147;Great, now I''m even more confused. I thought you were going to explain mobile first not make it worse.&#148; \r\n		It''s important to know that all these perspectives exist so that when discussing mobile first with your colleges you can understand up front that everyone will be expecting something different.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<h3>Time to align on Mobile First</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		One of the first things you should do is sit down with your group and define what &#147;Mobile First&#148; means to each of you, before everyone gets to far down the road. This means that we need to discuss it in\r\n		boarder terms instead of industry standards. So let''s talk about mobile first as a strategy, or a way of thinking.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<img src="img/articles/michael_stevens_mobile_first_baseline.png" alt="Mobile First Baseline - Michael Stevens" />\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		When we discuss mobile first as a strategy we are in fact proposing the creation of a product designed specifically for a mobile device. Weather that be an app, a mobile-only website, or a responsive based website our \r\n		end goal is to have an experience designed for mobile.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		&#147;But I don''t need a mobile website, I just want something out quick.&#148; Let''s face it, time equals money and nobody likes spending money, they like making it. So lets evaluate the word <strong>need</strong>.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		I have worked at a company called <a href="http://www.backcountry.com" target="_blank">Backcountry.com</a> since around 2006 and I have been around long enough to see the number of mobile users jump from basically zero to \r\n		about a third of their daily traffic. Now not to be obvious, but if a third of your traffic is coming from a mobile device, to make money you <strong>need</strong> a good experience on mobile. If mobile isn''t a \r\n		third of your traffic, one day it will be if not more. So think of mobile first as investing in the future.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<h3>So why start with mobile?</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		For some people it''s hard to understand why they need to design mobile first before they design anything else. To put it very clearly <strong>mobile forces you to focus on whats important</strong>. Eventually, everyone wants to be covered on everything. This potentially means\r\n		have multiple executions of the same thing out there that have to be built multiple times. The illustration below some of the problems we can run into if we design desktop first.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<img src="img/articles/michael_stevens_desktop_first.png" alt="Desktop First Illustration - Michael Stevens" />\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		As you can see from the illustration above, if you start off by designing for your largest media, you find that with each smaller device you face, trying to smash the concept into a smaller screen gets harder &amp; and harder. Now let''s take a look at the mobile first approach.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<img src="img/articles/michael_stevens_mobile_first.png" alt="Mobile First Illustration - Michael Stevens" />\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		By starting with the smaller media, you can see there the process would actually require fewer, if any changes between devices in order to get the concept to work.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<h3>Embrace the constraints</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		If there is one thing that mobile does well is that it demands thoughtful execution. Weather it''s the range of screen sizes from large to small or the limits of the users bandwidth, \r\n		mobile demands that we simplify &amp; prioritize. Often when your are used to communicating your message across a larger device you have plenty of space in which to do so, but when you\r\n		only have 320 by 568 pixels of space on a tiny handheld monitor, you better make sure that the content you surface is really needed. In a lot of ways this can be freeing for many people, \r\n		because they realize that some of the stuff which they would have included on a desktop version of their application simply isn''t so important that it needs to be incorporated on mobile or\r\n		if they try they will often find that the non-essential elements only serve to get in the way of the users real goal. \r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		<img src="img/articles/michael_stevens_snail_mobile_first.png" alt="" />\r\n	</p>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Often clients will discover that if something wasn''t needed on the mobile version, why would it be on the desktop version? Developers are often forced to build more simply\r\n		or architect their systems to be lighter because they devices aren''t capable of handling the load larger architectures would require. If the mobile site is build to be fast on\r\n		a slow connection, just image how fast it will be on a fast connection.\r\n	</p></div>', '5 minutes read', 1, '2014-05-28', 37, 2);
INSERT INTO `articles` VALUES(4, 'img/articles/michael_stevens_mobile_best_practices.png', 'Mobile Best Practices', 'Handset Design Guidelines', 'Entering the world of mobile can often be a learning experience for most of us. Even if we have designed for years on the desktop, mobile often offers new surprises and challenges we''ve never faced before.', '<div class="inner-container">\r\n	<h3>Crafting Mobile Content</h3>\r\n	<p>\r\n		Creating content for mobile can often seem unclear. Many people are simply content with reusing the content they''ve created for the desktop without \r\n		being mindful of the differences between mobile &amp; desktop users. With mobile users viewing and consuming content differently than desktop users it''s important\r\n		that we focus on some specific principals around mobile that will help the users consume our content on a mobile device.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<h4>Mobile Content Principals</h4>\r\n	<ul>\r\n		<li>Mobile Content should be short &amp; focused.</li>\r\n		<li>Remove Distractions, without sacraficing content.</li>\r\n		<li>Always retain the core message between mobile and desktop experiences.</li>\r\n	</ul>\r\n	<h4>Various Content Types</h4>\r\n	<p>\r\n		It''s also important to remember that when we say "content" we can actually be discussing multiple types of content, each with it''s own unique dynamics that can\r\n		effect how and what our users will experience. Below are some of the more common content types and how each of them can be optimized to insure a better mobile experience.\r\n	</p>\r\n	<div class="clear"></div>\r\n</div>', '5 minutes read', 1, '2014-05-28', 38, 2);
